President Biden delivered a speech in the East Room of the White House commemorating Juneteenth and signing it into law as a federal holiday. He emphasized the significance of Juneteenth as a day that marks the end of slavery and the beginning of America's work towards equality. President Biden also highlighted the ongoing efforts to combat racial discrimination and promote racial justice, including addressing housing disparities, increasing Black homeownership, supporting Black entrepreneurs, and investing in Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCUs). He stressed the importance of equity in various aspects of society, including healthcare, voting rights, and criminal justice. President Biden called for action on Juneteenth and encouraged Americans to get vaccinated against COVID-19. He also acknowledged the tragic deaths at Mother Emanuel Church in Charleston and emphasized the need to continue the work of rooting out hate and promoting racial justice. President Biden expressed his gratitude to the members of Congress, particularly the Congressional Black Caucus, for their efforts in making Juneteenth a federal holiday. He concluded his speech by signing the Juneteenth National Independence Day Act into law.